The sizes of CdTe@MIPs and CDs@NIPs were characterized by TEM (Fig. 2
                        ). As observed in Fig. 2, the sizes of CDs and CdTe were less than 10 nm, and the particle sizes of CdTe@MIPs and CDs@NIPs were approximately 90 nm and displayed spherical structure. Besides, the optical properties of CdTe@MIPs and CDs@NIPs were also investigated. Fluorescent spectra of CdTe@MIPs, CDs@NIPs, CdTe@MIPs/CDs@NIPs and eluant of CdTe@MIPs/CDs@NIPs were investigated and showed corresponding fluorescence properties respectively (showed in Fig. 3
                        ). The symmetric emission peaks at 680 nm and 520 nm of CdTe@MIPs/CDs@NIPs exactly matched with that of CdTe@MIPs and CDs@NIPs under excitation wavelength of 370 nm. This indicated that the SiO2 coating on the surface does not restrict the photoluminescence properties of CDs and CdTe because the SiO2 is optically transparent and inert. As a comparison, the fluorescence intensity of the eluant of sensor of CdTe@MIPs/CDs@NIPs was negative which indicating the CDs and CdTe were firmly embedded into the imprinting layers successfully and almost no free fluorescent quantum dots in the sensor solution.

A critical issue in developing any optical sensor is selectivity. Therefore, the selectivity of CdTe@MIPs/CDs@NIPs to kinds of analogues or interferents, including CTD, tetrodotoxin, bufotoxin, bee venom, Ca2+, Na+, Mg2+, and glucose, urea, uric acid, creatine, creatinine, cholesterol, phospholipid was investigated to evaluate practicability of the developed ratiometric platform for CTD detection (Fig. 8
                        ). As shown in Fig. 8, with addition of equal amount of the substances above respectively (1000 nM), fluorescence significantly quenched by CTD at 680 nm. Whereas others presented negative fluorescence response at 680 nm. During the whole process, the fluorescence intensity at 520 nm regard as internal reference was stable. This also confirmed that a large number of specific imprinting sites anchored on the sensor were perfectly matched with CTD based on the hydrogen bond interaction between the amine groups and CTD. The targets could be easily recombined with customized binding sites, but interferents seem less likely chance to access for the big differences in shape, size, and structure compared with CTD. Moreover, considering the complex composition in blood, tolerance limit investigation was carried out for common anions and cations to optimize the sensor more comprehensively. With the addition of very high levels of actively interfered ions to CTD detection platform, a high interference (10%) in the detection data for CTD was showed in Table 1
                        . The results manifested that CdTe@MIPs/CDs@NIPs sensor, even in the interference of plenty of relevant ions in internal environment, could be applied to determination of CTD in blood with good selectivity.
